 activities used by knights to hone their physical abilities: running, jumping, throwing, and vaulting. Finally, the Collectanea is the solemedieval text to provide extensive discussion of the design of arms and armour. This translation includes an illustrated introduction to Monte and his technical subject-matter, as well as a translation of Book 5 of Monte's De Dignoscendis Hominibus (1492), which overlaps much of the technical content of the Collectanea. JEFFREY L. FORGENG is curator of Arms and Armour and Medieval Art at the Worcester Art Museum, and teaches as Adjunct Professor of History at Worcester Polytechnic Institute.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary art and sciencexHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArms and Armour.  aAthletics.  aCollectanea.  aCombat Techniques.  aFifteenth-Century.  aKnighthood.  aMartial Arts.  aMilitary Techniques.  aMilitary Treatise.  aPietro Monte.  aSoldier.  aWeaponry.1 aForgeng, Jeffrey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787441859?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787441859423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787441859/original  a978-3-11-143106-2  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles